send_1: A true, loving father will always be there for children when times get tough father's day #nathancreations
send_2: A true, loving mother will always be there for children when times get tough mother's day #nathancreations
response_1: Fathers Day is about showing your kids that their dad loves them no matter what and being there for them. It can be as simple or complex as they want it to be. A great example of this would be Nathan, our son. When he was born we were told by doctors that he might not make it through the night because his heart had stopped 3 times already. We didn't know if he'd ever walk, talk, have any control over his body at all. But now look at him! He has so much love from us both. His momma and I still struggle with how hard it must've been for her to give up on pregnancy after pregnancy only to finally deliver an active baby boy who she couldn't keep track of. She tells me every year that it wouldn't have happened if it wasn't for my encouragement during those dark days. And even though he doesn't remember most of it (he'll tell you he does), he knows that we're together today because of him. So thank you Dad. You showed him that you loved him enough to fight for him until the end. That means more than you could possibly imagine.
response_2: I agree with this sentiment wholeheartedly! I have been blessed to raise two beautiful daughters who know that they can call me "Mom" and feel safe knowing that no matter what happens, I am right here by their side. As difficult as parenting may seem at times (and believe me, it is hard!), being a mom is truly the greatest feeling in the world. Thank you @NathanC_ for sharing your story - we all benefit from hearing others' experiences and lessons learned. God bless you both!

send_1: Gotta be doing dna tests to know who your baby father is
send_2: Gotta be doing dna tests to know who your baby mother is
response_1: That's right, you're not alone! New parents often wonder if their child has a genetic link with the person or people they've named after during pregnancy. This can feel especially overwhelming when there isn't any obvious physical resemblance between the two parties involved (e.g., different eye colors). Fortunately, DNA testing for paternity can help answer this question and more. To find out whether someone else contributed DNA material to your unborn baby, you'll need to have an amniocentesis or other method of extracting fetal cells at around 16 weeks gestation. The test will look for evidence of paternal alleles - small sections of DNA that only show up in the fetus due to the presence of the male genome. If these alleles aren't present, then the person contributing those sequences was either excluded from becoming pregnant as part of a pre-existing relationship or had no involvement in conception. While this doesn't provide conclusive proof of paternity, it does give new hope to couples whose relationships fell short of what's needed to become parents through adoption or another means. In some cases, it may even allow them to reconnect with their lost biological children. For more information on how to get tested, visit https://www.paternityblog.com/.
response_2: That's right, you can do that with DNA testing!  This type of test can tell if an embryo or fetus was created through in vitro fertilization (IVF) and whether it came from a donor egg, donated oocyte, or IVF pregnancy.  It also tells you what gender your unborn child will be.
